= Carousel =

A JavaScript carousel.

== USAGE ==

Create your DOM like so:

  <div id="carousel">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="wrapper">
        <div>Number 1</div>
        <div>Number 2</div>
        <div>Number 3</div>
        <div>Number 4</div>
        <div>Number 5</div>
        <div>Number 6</div>
        <div>Number 7</div>
        <div>Number 8</div>
        <div>Number 9</div>
        <div>Number 10</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <a href="#previous">back</a>
    <a href="#next">Next</a>
  </div>

The #carousel element is the parent element.

Inside it, the .container element is the viewable area for the carousel. The .wrapper
element is the element that allows for scrolling. Under the .wrapper element are your
carousel items.

Make sure to include two links, one with href="#next" and one with href="#previous",
since the carousel will be looking for them somewhere within the parent element.

Then instantiate a new Carousel, passing in the id attribute of your parent div:

  new Pivotal.Carousel('carousel');

See the source for options that can be passed in.